,Recommended,431600,34314742,Posted: 17 August,all,Bradlero,"This game..... THIS GAME!Where to begin.... I've mentioned this before in my reviews about racing games/sims, I'll say it again, I primarily play racing and sim type games on PC and console, if there's been a racing game released on either in the last 30 years I've likely played it. In regards to sims; Assetto Corsa, Project Cars, rFactor 2, R3E.... you name it, I own them all, and play them all. Automobilista has to be my favorite out of all of them!Here's why;Automobilista is a fantastic racing sim. Reiza has taken rFactor 1 and built on that to the point that it feels like a new experience. Essentially what we have here is rFactor 1 with all the best mods included and updated, plus many little tweaks here and there to bring one of the best racing experiences available on the PC at this time.Sure the graphics may not be on par with something like AC or PCars, but this is a DX9 title and for that era of game engine, the visuals certainly do more then enough to appear convincing and many of the car models included as well as available via modding are faithfully reproduced inside and out. The full daytime spectrum is available when racing from dawn till dusk and overnight, unfortunately weather is currently not an option but I dont find I miss that too much since the simulation is so engrossing in other ways.By default the game ships with some of the most diverse racing series available in a game and this is great as it allows you to dip your toes into something you may not have otherwise tried. From stock cars, to Porsche GT3 cars, to nearly EVERY era of Formula 1 cars and Trophy Trucks to Karts, this game has it all. Oh yeah.... The Formula cars.... Automobilista has a car from nearly every era of Formula one, and this is awesome! Im a big F1 fan, so its really cool to be able to drive all the diff car styles throughout the history of the sport when you please. As far as track content goes the included list is lacking.... it's mostly made up of random Brazilian tracks that no one really knows or cares to know.... There are a few highlights thou, particularly both old and current configurations of Hockenheim and Imola (both of which I love), It's super cool to take a modern car down the original 72 layout of Imola!! I also love the addition of the Montreal GP circuit from Canada (I'm a Canadian eh!) so i can relate to that track IRL.Reiza has also released some great DLC in the form of new locations, all of which are faithfully recreated.The physics are some of the best in a sim game, even with all the other aforementioned heavy hitting sim titles I still find myself coming back to this game time and time again.... It's just the most fun, and I find the driving model to be spot on with most of the vehicles both included and mods. The FFB is great and the AI is really really smart, probably the best of all sims I've seen yet.Then there's the mods.... This game, like AC and many others available is made exceptional through the mods. In particular there is a track pack with 24 additional circuits by a guy named Patrick you can find on The RaceDept website that is so good its basically considered an official part of the game. It has a lot of the tracks you'd expect to see in a sim such as Monza, Spa, Laguna Seca, Nurburgring, Road America, Road Atlanta, etc. They are all made to the same level of quality as the provided Reiza circuits as well. Simply a must have. Then theres the available cars and series addons..... GTS, WTCC, Formula 1 (skins), CART, it goes on and on. Not the largest mod pool available yet but its growing and the quality of many of them are really really good.BOTTOM LINE; If you love sim racing, do yourself a favor and grab this game! It is hands down one of the best. If you can, try and grab the DLC as well in a bundle, it goes on sale at times.11/10 would buy again."
