,Recommended,431600,34579346,Posted: 29 August,all,pavig,"For my sim racing friends: pick this up with the season pass while it's on sale. It may look oldschool but for a proper driving simulator it's actually really fun. Physics and force feedback are up there with the best in class... but there are plenty of sims that can say that. This one beats them by providing the full package out of the box - the stuff you actually enjoy in driving games, and lots of it. This is particularly the case if you miss a quality single player experience. (There's MP too but I haven't tried that.)It has a fantastic comprehensive library of cars (including some unique classes) and tons of tracks and variations, which all feel very different. Every class has a full championship available, some several. Racing against AI is actually pretty good, with convincing 3 wide stock car action, an ai spotter on the radio, and real safety cars and flag rules. Glorified lawn mower 1 gear rental carts feel like rental carts, 70s muscle cars feel like they should, modern stock cars (particularly the aussie and brasilian formats) are especially satisfying. The insane open wheel and dirt cars, even trucks! are all convincing. This is also the only sim I have played where they sixties formula 1 cars drive like a modern evolution of the punishing GPL engine. As for F1, no licenses, but you can drive representatives of major format from the sixties onwards on historically matched track variants. Awesome. :)I'm kicking myself for having bought it a few days ago for full price, but after putting a few hours in I can see it's worth every penny. If you are an even occasional sim racer you'd be nuts to pass this up during the sale given the value here. I can see the thirty or so championship seasons on offer being my go-to offline racing kick for some time. :)"
